When You Run: kubectl create pod my-app
YOU â†’ kubectl â†’ API Server â†’ etcd â†’ Scheduler â†’ kubelet â†’ Pod Running

STEP-BY-STEP FLOW
STEP 1: You Make the Request
kubectl create pod my-app --image=nginx
What happens: kubectl sends HTTP request to API Server

STEP 2: API Server (Reception Desk)
API Server receives request
â”œâ”€â”€ Authentication: "Who are you?"
â”œâ”€â”€ Authorization: "Can you create pods?"
â”œâ”€â”€ Admission Control: "Is your request valid?"
â””â”€â”€ If OK â†’ Store in etcd
Status: Pod created with state = "Pending"

STEP 3: etcd (Hotel Database)
etcd stores:
{
  "pod": "my-app",
  "status": "Pending",
  "node": "unassigned",
  "image": "nginx"
}

STEP 4: Scheduler (Room Assignment Manager)
Scheduler watches etcd for unassigned pods
â”œâ”€â”€ Finds: my-app (status=Pending, node=unassigned)
â”œâ”€â”€ Checks all nodes: node1, node2, node3
â”œâ”€â”€ Picks best node: node2 (has resources)
â””â”€â”€ Updates etcd: my-app â†’ node2
Status: Pod scheduled to node2

STEP 5: kubelet on node2 (Floor Supervisor)
kubelet watches etcd for pods assigned to its node
â”œâ”€â”€ Sees: my-app assigned to me
â”œâ”€â”€ Pulls image: docker pull nginx
â”œâ”€â”€ Creates container: docker run nginx
â”œâ”€â”€ Assigns IP: 10.244.2.5
â””â”€â”€ Reports back: "Pod is Running"
Status: Pod = "Running"

STEP 6: kube-proxy (Phone System)
kube-proxy updates networking rules
â”œâ”€â”€ Pod IP: 10.244.2.5 is reachable
â”œâ”€â”€ Service discovery: my-app can be found
â””â”€â”€ Load balancing: Traffic can reach pod

STEP 7: Controller Manager (Operations Manager)
Controller Manager monitors:
â”œâ”€â”€ "Is my-app still running?" âœ…
â”œâ”€â”€ "Does it match desired state?" âœ…
â”œâ”€â”€ "If it dies, recreate it" (for Deployments)
â””â”€â”€ Continuous monitoring loop

VISUAL TIMELINE
Time: 0ms    â†’ kubectl command sent
Time: 10ms   â†’ API Server validates & stores in etcd
Time: 50ms   â†’ Scheduler picks node2
Time: 100ms  â†’ kubelet starts pulling image
Time: 5000ms â†’ Image pulled, container started
Time: 5500ms â†’ Pod reports "Running"
Time: 6000ms â†’ kube-proxy updates networking

QUICK STATUS CHECK
Check what's happening:
kubectl get pods -w    # Watch real-time changes
kubectl describe pod my-app    # See the events
You'll see:
0s   Scheduled    Pod assigned to node2
2s   Pulling      Pulling image "nginx"
8s   Pulled       Successfully pulled image
10s  Created      Created container
12s  Started      Started container

WHAT IF SOMETHING FAILS?
Scenario 1: No Available Nodes
API Server âœ… â†’ etcd âœ… â†’ Scheduler âŒ (no nodes with resources)
Status: Pod stays "Pending"
Scenario 2: Image Pull Fails
API Server âœ… â†’ etcd âœ… â†’ Scheduler âœ… â†’ kubelet âŒ (can't pull image)
Status: Pod = "ImagePullBackOff"
Scenario 3: API Server Down
kubectl â†’ API Server âŒ
Result: "connection refused"

THE HOTEL ANALOGY IN ACTION

Guest calls hotel â†’ kubectl create pod
Reception takes booking â†’ API Server validates
Booking recorded â†’ etcd storage
Manager assigns room â†’ Scheduler picks node
Floor supervisor prepares room â†’ kubelet runs container
Phone system updated â†’ kube-proxy configures networking
Guest checks in successfully â†’ Pod status = "Running"
